&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Corrosion&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Corrosion&lt;/strong&gt; is the chemical process in which metals deteriorate due to their interaction with the environment, often involving oxidation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The formation of green patina (plaque) on copper, rusting of iron, and blackening of silver are examples of corrosion caused by exposure to moisture, oxygen, or sulfur compounds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Corrosion is typically a slow process that occurs over time, depending on the environmental conditions and the type of metal.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Preventive measures like galvanization, painting, or coating metals are often used to protect them from corrosion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Corrosion can lead to significant economic losses as it damages infrastructure, machinery, and other metal-based objects.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Oxidation:&lt;/strong&gt; It is a chemical reaction where a substance loses electrons, often in the presence of oxygen, leading to the formation of oxides.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Galvanization:&lt;/strong&gt; A process of applying a protective zinc coating to steel or iron to prevent rusting.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Patina Formation:&lt;/strong&gt; Copper reacts with carbon dioxide, water, and atmospheric pollutants to form a green protective layer of copper carbonate over time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rusting:&lt;/strong&gt; Iron reacts with oxygen and moisture to form reddish-brown hydrated iron oxides, commonly known as rust.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Silver Tarnishing:&lt;/strong&gt; Silver reacts with sulfur compounds in the air to form black silver sulfide, leading to discoloration.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;[M&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;L&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;T&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;-2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span align-items:=&quot;&quot; display:=&quot;&quot; gap:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mechanical energy&lt;/strong&gt; is the sum of potential energy and kinetic energy of an object. It represents the energy possessed by an object due to its motion and position.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;The dimensional formula is derived from the formula for energy. Energy is expressed as the ability of an object to do work, and work is calculated using the formula: &lt;strong&gt;Work = Force &amp;times; Distance.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;Force is given by &lt;strong&gt;mass &amp;times; acceleration&lt;/strong&gt;, which has the dimensional formula of &lt;strong&gt;[M][L][T⁻&amp;sup2;]&lt;/strong&gt;. Distance has the dimensional formula &lt;strong&gt;[L]&lt;/strong&gt;. Multiplying these, the dimensional formula for work or energy becomes &lt;strong&gt;[M][L&amp;sup2;][T⁻&amp;sup2;]&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;The dimensional formula of&lt;strong&gt; &lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;[M&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;L&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;T&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;position: relative;  line-height: 0; vertical-align: baseline; top: -0.5em;font-size:10.5px;&quot;&gt;-2&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;]&lt;/span&gt; &lt;/strong&gt;is thus the correct representation of mechanical energy, which includes both kinetic and potential energy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;The options provided in the question are as follows:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Option 1: &lt;strong&gt;[ML&amp;sup2;T⁻&amp;sup3;]&lt;/strong&gt; - This is incorrect as the time dimension in this formula is not correct.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Option 2: &lt;strong&gt;[M&amp;sup1;L&amp;sup2;]&lt;/strong&gt; - This is incorrect as it does not include the time dimension, which is essential for energy.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Option 3: &lt;strong&gt;[M&amp;sup2;L&amp;sup2;T⁻&amp;sup1;]&lt;/strong&gt; - This is incorrect as the mass and time dimensions are not accurate.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Option 4: &lt;strong&gt;[M&amp;sup1;L&amp;sup2;T⁻&amp;sup2;]&lt;/strong&gt; - This is correct as it accurately represents the dimensional formula for mechanical energy.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span align-items:=&quot;&quot; display:=&quot;&quot; gap:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Types of Mechanical Energy:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Kinetic Energy:&lt;/strong&gt; The energy possessed by a body due to its motion. It is given by the formula: &lt;strong&gt;KE = &amp;frac12;mv&amp;sup2;&lt;/strong&gt;, where &lt;strong&gt;m&lt;/strong&gt; is the mass and &lt;strong&gt;v&lt;/strong&gt; is the velocity.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Potential Energy:&lt;/strong&gt; The energy possessed by a body due to its position or configuration. It is given by the formula: &lt;strong&gt;PE = mgh&lt;/strong&gt;, where &lt;strong&gt;m&lt;/strong&gt; is the mass, &lt;strong&gt;g&lt;/strong&gt; is the acceleration due to gravity, and &lt;strong&gt;h&lt;/strong&gt; is the height.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dimensional Formula Analysis:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;The dimensional formula represents the physical dimensions of a quantity in terms of base units, such as mass (&lt;strong&gt;M&lt;/strong&gt;), length (&lt;strong&gt;L&lt;/strong&gt;), and time (&lt;strong&gt;T&lt;/strong&gt;).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;For mechanical energy, combining the dimensions of force (&lt;strong&gt;[MLT⁻&amp;sup2;]&lt;/strong&gt;) and distance (&lt;strong&gt;[L]&lt;/strong&gt;) gives the formula &lt;strong&gt;[ML&amp;sup2;T⁻&amp;sup2;]&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Mechanical Energy:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;Mechanical energy is utilized in various fields such as engineering, construction, and transportation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;Examples include machines, vehicles, power generation, and even natural phenomena like waterfalls.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;It is also studied in physics to understand the principles of energy conservation and dynamics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span align-items:=&quot;&quot; display:=&quot;&quot; gap:=&quot;&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Energy Conservation:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;The law of conservation of energy states that &lt;strong&gt;energy can neither be created nor destroyed&lt;/strong&gt;. It can only be transformed from one form to another.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;Mechanical energy can be converted into other forms of energy, such as electrical energy, heat energy, etc.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Units of Energy:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SI Unit:&lt;/strong&gt; The standard unit of energy is the &lt;strong&gt;joule (J).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li data-end=&quot;&quot; data-start=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Other Units:&lt;/strong&gt; Energy is also measured in calories, kilowatt-hours (kWh), and electron volts (eV).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cytoplasm, nucleoplasm, and other organelles&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Protoplasm&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It is the living part of the cell, which comprises different cellular organelles.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a jelly-like, colorless, transparent, and viscous living substance present within the cell wall.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The term protoplasm was proposed in the year 1835 and is known as the primary substance, as it is responsible for various living processes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It was believed that cells were containers of protoplasm.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;However, the concept could not explain the origin of structures formed within the cell, primarily the nucleus.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The cytoplasm is the initial component of protoplasm, which is found between the cell membrane and the cell nucleus in a eukaryotic cell.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;In the cell, a cytoplasm plays a vital role in maintaining the cell environment, maintains the shape of cells, and also stores substances required by the organelle.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The nucleus is the second component of the protoplasm, which stores the genetic information of an organism.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Ribosomes are also found in the nucleus, which is essential for the production of proteins in the cell.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Prokaryotes contain a nucleoid instead of a nucleus where all the genetic information is found.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Proteins, fats, enzymes, hormones, all make up the protoplasm.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, Option 4 is correct.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These are either dissolved or suspended in the water component of the protoplasm.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Alpha cells&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Alpha cells are one of the four primary types of islet cells found in the pancreas.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These cells secrete &lt;strong&gt;glucagon&lt;/strong&gt;, a peptide hormone that primarily raises blood glucose levels.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Glucagon works by stimulating the liver to convert glycogen into glucose (glycogenolysis) and releasing it into the bloodstream.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Alpha cells play a crucial role in maintaining glucose homeostasis, especially during fasting or low blood sugar conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The secretion of glucagon is regulated by blood glucose levels; it increases when blood glucose levels fall and decreases when they rise.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Beta cells&lt;/strong&gt;: These cells secrete insulin, a hormone that lowers blood glucose levels by facilitating glucose uptake by cells.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Delta cells&lt;/strong&gt;: These cells produce somatostatin, a hormone that inhibits the secretion of both insulin and glucagon.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;PP cells&lt;/strong&gt;: Also known as pancreatic polypeptide cells, they secrete pancreatic polypeptide, which helps regulate pancreatic enzyme secretion and gastrointestinal motility.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Glucose homeostasis&lt;/strong&gt;: It refers to the balanced regulation of blood sugar levels, primarily controlled by insulin (lowers glucose) and glucagon (raises glucose).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Diabetes mellitus&lt;/strong&gt;: A chronic condition characterized by the inability to properly regulate blood glucose, often due to beta-cell dysfunction or insulin resistance.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Rheostat&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;rheostat&lt;/strong&gt; is a variable resistor used in electrical circuits to adjust the resistance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is commonly used to control the flow of current in a circuit and thus regulate voltage or power.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Rheostats are constructed with a resistive wire wound around an insulating core, allowing for resistance adjustment by moving a slider or wiper.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They are widely utilized in applications such as dimming lights, controlling motor speed, and tuning radios.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike fixed resistors, rheostats offer the flexibility of altering resistance dynamically during operation.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Resistor:&lt;/strong&gt; A passive electrical component that provides resistance to control current in a circuit. Fixed resistors have a set resistance value, unlike variable resistors like rheostats.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Potentiometer:&lt;/strong&gt; Another variable resistor, similar to a rheostat but typically used for measuring or dividing voltage rather than controlling current directly.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ohm&amp;rsquo;s Law:&lt;/strong&gt; The fundamental principle governing the relationship between voltage (V), current (I), and resistance (R) in an electrical circuit, represented by the equation V = IR.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Rheostats:&lt;/strong&gt; Besides light dimming and motor control, rheostats are used in experimental setups to test circuits and components under varying resistance conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Difference Between Rheostat and Transformer:&lt;/strong&gt; While a rheostat alters resistance to control current, a transformer is an electrical device that changes voltage levels through electromagnetic induction.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Frost Action&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Frost Action&lt;/strong&gt; is a physical weathering process where water enters cracks in rocks, freezes, and expands, causing the rock to fracture and break apart. It does not involve chemical changes, making it a part of physical weathering and not chemical weathering.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hydration:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a chemical weathering process in which minerals absorb water and undergo chemical changes, often leading to expansion and weakening of the rock.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, this is a part of chemical weathering.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Oxidation:&lt;/strong&gt; This chemical weathering process involves the reaction of oxygen with minerals, particularly iron, forming oxides (e.g., rust). It weakens the rock over time.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, this is a part of chemical weathering.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Carbonation:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a chemical weathering process where carbon dioxide reacts with water to form carbonic acid, which then dissolves minerals like calcium carbonate in rocks such as limestone.&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, this is a part of chemical weathering.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Thus, Frost Action is NOT a part of chemical weathering as it involves physical processes rather than chemical reactions.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Physical Weathering:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Physical weathering involves the breakdown of rocks through mechanical processes such as temperature changes, abrasion, and freeze-thaw cycles.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Frost Action:&lt;/strong&gt; A common physical weathering process, particularly in cold climates, where water freezes inside cracks and expands, breaking the rock apart.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Other processes include thermal expansion, exfoliation, and abrasion caused by wind, water, or glaciers.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Chemical Weathering:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Chemical weathering involves the decomposition or alteration of rocks due to chemical reactions between minerals and external agents like water, oxygen, and acids.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hydration:&lt;/strong&gt; Minerals absorb water, causing structural changes, expansion, and weakening of the rock.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Oxidation:&lt;/strong&gt; Oxygen reacts with iron or other minerals to form oxides, leading to rust formation and weakening of rocks.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Carbonation:&lt;/strong&gt; Carbonic acid dissolves minerals like calcium carbonate, especially in limestone and marble, leading to features like caves and sinkholes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Key Differences Between Physical and Chemical Weathering:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Physical Weathering:&lt;/strong&gt; Does not alter the chemical composition of rocks; examples include frost action and abrasion.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Chemical Weathering:&lt;/strong&gt; Alters the chemical composition of rocks, leading to decomposition; examples include hydration, oxidation, and carbonation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Both types of weathering work together to break down rocks and form soil over time.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples of Chemical Weathering:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hydration:&lt;/strong&gt; Feldspar minerals in granite absorb water and transform into clay minerals.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Oxidation:&lt;/strong&gt; Iron-rich minerals in basalt react with oxygen to form rust.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Carbonation:&lt;/strong&gt; Carbon dioxide in rainwater dissolves limestone, creating caves and karst topography.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Impact of Weathering:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Weathering contributes to soil formation, nutrient cycling, and landscape modification.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It can weaken structures like buildings and bridges over time, requiring maintenance and reinforcement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Weathering Study:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Understanding weathering processes helps in construction planning and selecting materials resistant to weathering.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It assists geologists in studying the history of landscapes and predicting geological hazards like landslides.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pepsinogen (converted to pepsin)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pepsinogen&lt;/strong&gt; is secreted by the chief cells of the stomach and is an inactive precursor enzyme (zymogen).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is converted into its active form, &lt;strong&gt;pepsin&lt;/strong&gt;, in the presence of hydrochloric acid (HCl) secreted by the parietal cells.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pepsin&lt;/strong&gt; is the primary enzyme responsible for breaking down proteins into smaller peptides in the acidic environment of the stomach.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The activation of pepsinogen ensures that protein digestion begins in the stomach, which is essential for nutrient absorption in later stages of digestion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The stomach&amp;rsquo;s acidic pH (approximately 1.5&amp;ndash;3.5) is crucial for the activation and function of pepsin.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Chief Cells:&lt;/strong&gt; Specialized cells located in the stomach lining that produce pepsinogen and gastric lipase.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hydrochloric Acid (HCl):&lt;/strong&gt; Secreted by parietal cells in the stomach, HCl lowers the pH and facilitates the activation of pepsinogen into pepsin.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Protein Digestion:&lt;/strong&gt; Proteins are broken into smaller peptides by pepsin, and later into amino acids by enzymes in the small intestine like trypsin and chymotrypsin.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Trypsinogen vs. Pepsinogen:&lt;/strong&gt; Trypsinogen is secreted by the pancreas and activated into trypsin in the small intestine, while pepsinogen is activated into pepsin in the stomach.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Zymogen Activation:&lt;/strong&gt; Zymogens like pepsinogen are inactive forms of enzymes, activated under specific conditions to prevent self-digestion of the tissue that produces them.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Magnetic fields are completely expelled from the interior of the material.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Meissner effect is a defining property of superconductors where magnetic fields are expelled from the interior of the material during the transition to the superconducting state.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This phenomenon occurs below a critical temperature (Tc) unique to each superconducting material.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The expulsion of magnetic fields is a result of the superconducting material forming perfect diamagnetic properties.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;As the superconducting state is achieved, the material cancels the internal magnetic field by generating surface currents that oppose the applied magnetic field.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is distinct from perfect conductivity, as it implies both zero electrical resistance and zero magnetic field within the material.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Superconductivity:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Superconductivity is a quantum mechanical phenomenon where certain materials exhibit zero electrical resistance and expel magnetic fields below a critical temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It was discovered in 1911 by Heike Kamerlingh Onnes in mercury cooled to 4.2 K.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Applications include MRI machines, particle accelerators, and quantum computing.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Meissner Effect:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Named after Walther Meissner and Robert Ochsenfeld, who discovered it in 1933.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It demonstrates the fundamental difference between superconductors and perfect conductors.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The magnetic field is expelled entirely from the bulk of the material, not just reduced.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Type I vs Type II Superconductors:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Type I superconductors completely expel magnetic fields and are typically elemental metals.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Type II superconductors allow partial penetration of magnetic fields in the form of vortices and are often alloys or compounds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Critical Temperature (Tc):&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The temperature below which a material becomes superconducting.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Varies widely among materials, from below 1 K in some metals to above 100 K in high-temperature superconductors.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;O₂&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In a chemical reaction, the &lt;strong&gt;limiting reagent is the reactant that is completely consumed first, limiting the amount of product formed&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The reaction provided is &lt;strong&gt;2H₂ + O₂ &amp;rarr; 2H₂O&lt;/strong&gt;, where 2 moles of H₂ react with 1 mole of O₂ to form 2 moles of water (H₂O).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Given 5 moles of H₂ and 2 moles of O₂, the stoichiometric ratio is analyzed: 5 moles H₂ would require (5/2) = 2.5 moles of O₂, but only 2 moles of O₂ are available.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Since O₂ is insufficient to react with all the H₂, it is the limiting reagent.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The excess reactant in this scenario is H₂, as not all 5 moles of H₂ can react due to the shortage of O₂.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Limiting Reagent:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The reactant that determines the maximum amount of product formed in a chemical reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is completely consumed during the reaction, leaving other reactants in excess.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Stoichiometry:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The quantitative relationship between reactants and products in a balanced chemical equation.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It helps in determining the mole ratio required for a reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Mole Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A mole represents 6.022 &amp;times; 10&amp;sup2;&amp;sup3; particles (Avogadro&amp;#39;s number) of a substance.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Moles are used to express quantities in chemical reactions for easy stoichiometric calculations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Excess Reagent:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The reactant that remains unreacted after the limiting reagent is completely consumed.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In this case, H₂ is the excess reagent.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Applications of Limiting Reagent Concept:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Used in industrial chemical processes to optimize reactant usage.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Helps prevent wastage and reduce costs by determining the exact proportions of reactants.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;CO and CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;Law of Multiple Proportions &lt;/strong&gt;states that when two elements combine to form more than one compound, the masses of one element that combine with a fixed mass of the other are in a simple whole-number ratio.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Carbon monoxide (CO) and carbon dioxide (CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;) are compounds of carbon and oxygen that follow this law.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In CO, the ratio of carbon to oxygen by mass is 12:16, while in CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;, it is 12:32. The oxygen mass ratio between CO and CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; is 16:32, which simplifies to 1:2.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This simple whole-number ratio (1:2) illustrates the Law of Multiple Proportions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The law was proposed by John Dalton in 1804 and is one of the basic principles of stoichiometry in chemistry.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Law of Multiple Proportions:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is one of the fundamental laws of chemical combination in chemistry.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This law applies when two elements form more than one compound, such as CO and CO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;, or SO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; and SO&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The law emphasizes the discrete nature of chemical combinations, underscoring the concept of fixed proportions in compounds.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Examples of the Law:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Water (H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O) and hydrogen peroxide (H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;) &amp;mdash; The ratio of oxygen masses is 1:2.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Sulfur dioxide (SO&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;) and sulfur trioxide (SO&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;) &amp;mdash; The ratio of oxygen masses is 2:3.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;John Dalton:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;He is known as the &amp;quot;Father of Modern Chemistry&amp;quot; for his Atomic Theory, which includes the Law of Multiple Proportions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;His work laid the foundation for modern stoichiometry and molecular chemistry.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Stoichiometry:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is the quantitative study of reactants and products in a chemical reaction.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The Law of Multiple Proportions is a cornerstone of stoichiometric calculations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
